\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-461\li461\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin461\itap0\pararsid752558 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Can I ask your name?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Rose Embleton.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 What was your year of marriage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Oh - 1926.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 What year were you born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 1899, November the first. 1899.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Where were you born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 London Road, Gayward Street. Elephant and Castle.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Do you remember how many years you lived in the house you were born in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Well not very long 'cos we went
 to live with our Granny in Bower Street. That was in - same as London Road and my granny lived in her house fifty years to the day she - she died.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Why did you live with your grandmother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Well we all went to - we all - my mum went to live there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 With the whole family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Yes. Yes. My granny had the house and my mother had the rooms - on top.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 How old do you think you were when you went to your grandmothers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Oh, I suppose I was about - twelve months to - two years, 'cos my sister
 was born within that time. She was - there's thirteen months between me and my sister. And there was thirteen months between my sister and - the boy. But my mother lost the boy when he was nine months old like through fits how they used to have these fit
s. So that was that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 So you've only got one sister?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 
Well I don't know where she is now because it's a long since I seen her but - so - I know she used she used to live at Walworth somewhere but - whether she's moved from there I don't know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Do you know how old your father was when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 
Oh he was only a young man. Well my mother - my mother really - as - the year as I worked - I was twenty and my mother was thirty. So - that's all I know, that my mother was - she got married w
hen she was young. But - but as for me father, I - I don't know how old he was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 You think he was quite a young man?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 He was a young man, oh yes, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Do you know where he came from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Oh Ireland. Dublin.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Did he come over as a child or as a young man?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 
Oh he come over as a child - like. And - he was over here I think and - it wasn't 'til later he brought his mother and - 'cos she couldn't hardly speak - she spoke more of a - Irish brogue or a - you know what I mean, that - o
h nice old lady she was but - nice old lady. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 What was your father's occupation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 
He was - he was a - to do with the horses, a stableman as you could call 'em. He worked at - now when we had the - when they had the - horse buses, I think in t
he Old Kent Road was - Tilling's - can't really - Tillingly's but - he used to be, then he used to go to the sales at the Elephant and Castle and - where every Monday and Thursday used to be - a - sales for horses. Yes. Then if he - if anybody like bought
 so many horses and he did, he used to have to take 'em - like and they used to come out from the stables on the -on the loops and he'd - he'd - like walk 'em to where they had to go. Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Is that the only job you remember him doing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 He never done no more. No, he was always a - to do with the horses.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Did he ever have any part time jobs or casual jobs besides that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Who?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Your father.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 No, not as I know of. 'Course he was - well I can't say that - he wasn't a very good fath
er. Not with my old mum, she was a good woman. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Was your father in the war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 
No. No. Because when I was eleven - I was eleven, I think I was eleven, well - getting on for thirteen, my sister was - getting on for twelve then, he left home and 
he took every penny my mother had. Pinched every penny she had. She was hardworking woman. Yes. And my old mum used to go to work, my old granny like - she - this morning she go up and make the beds and she heard the door go and he hollered out, he said, 
S
usan. Always called my old granny Black Eyed Susan, from me old grandfather. Susan, tell Tops I - I met another. He went out with what he took out the drawers and that and he took my old mum had - so many sovereigns under the - the carpet in her front roo
m
 what they had them days, and - he went away and he took every penny. Well when - when my mum came home from work on the night time my old granny said, she said, James has gone away Tps. She's gone upstairs and come down, she said, well he's took every pe
n
ny I got. And 'course - I had a very good aunt. And - like - with her first children was twins. Well she lost 'em. She never had no more after that. Well she always looked after me and my sister. And 'course - my mother went over to her, she said, he's go
ne and - she says, get out a warrant for him, you know. My mother said, no, let him go. 'Cos he used to come home and - pull her, 'cos she had a fine head of hair, used to pull her all round the room like of a night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 You - remember that even as a girl?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 
I - well - me and my sister. And - any old how - my mother said, no, let him go, she said, perhaps I'll be better off without him. And my aunt said, all right. Well of course she - really - looked after me and my sister like you know, having no chil
dren of her own, always helped my mother with us two. But we always had a good life you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 You didn't see much of your father after that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 We - we never seen him for thirty odd years. Well I never. But it was after this last war - he went and 
knocked on my mother's door. And - I weren't - well I wasn't there anymore, my mother lived with my sister. And - they - they - he come to the door with my uncle, he was a - he was in - well years ago he used to be in the - Fifth Lancers and - in the band
,
 'cos he never got married 'til late in life and 'course, he always knew where he was. And of course I suppose after the war - he was - took - took him round to my mother's 'cos he knew where we lived - where my mother lived with my sister. 'Course my poo
r
 old mum's opened the door 'course - my uncle says - that's all I can say well what's my mother told me. My uncle said - Tops, I've brought you a stranger. And - my father said to her, do you remember me Alice? Always call her Alice my father. 'Course soo
n
 as she heard his voice she said, get away from here. Get away - how comes you coming here, after all them years, thirty odd years? Well of course - on the night time - knock comes on my door, it's my sister. So I said, whatever's the matter? Oh, she said
,
 Bella - 'cos they never call me Rose, it's always Bella, so she said, Bella, she said, you don't know who's turned up today? I said, I don't know, I said, well who? So she said, dad. I said, dad? I said, I'd like to see the bastard, I said, excuse me, I 
s
aid, I'd kill him. So she said, oh, she said, mum's in a terrible state she said. It's so upset her. So - any old how I said, all right, I'll come down. I went down, I said - oh, she said, Bella, she said, what a - you know, God, she said, when he spoke. 
S
he said, I wouldn't have known - I wouldn't have known him. She said, but how he spoke, he speaks like you. Cor, I said, I'd like to have been here. I said, I know where I could land one of them. Of course - like - after that no more, we never heard no mo
r
e 'til - he was - like his - he'd been took ill. I think he went away to the Welsh mines and I think and he lived with a woman, know what I mean. Don't really know but that's surmising. Because his landlady, this landlady sent for the priest. Well I said,
 he ought to have a priest, he was never a good - he sent for the priest for the last - you know, rites and everything, what he wanted. But there you are. Well that's the last - that was him. And that's me life of me father.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 You didn't really know your father well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 No. Only as we was kids. Yes, but he was a - no, he was a real right - really right bad man, he was really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Was he good to the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Oh, there was only one he -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Was he good to you children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Oh to me, to my sister, but - he'd always go for my sister, I don't really know. I don't know, really know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Was he an affectionate sort of man, did you feel very close to him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Oh, he was very - he wasn't - no, he never made a lot of fuss of us, no. But - I will sa
y that - if ever there was any trouble like such at school one day he did come round to the school for us, know what I mean. And I was always a bit scared of him because he - he could be a very - very nasty kind of a man, but he come through and - that wa
s
 because - one of the teachers at the school had hit my sister and she suffered with her ears, she'd been under - like operations with her earns and - I'm going through to put - and I used to be the - the monitor for the - the headmistress at the school a
n
d I used to go and put her potatoes on, that's about half past eleven and as I walked through I could see this Miss Sheffield - Miss Bates, I can never forget - I can always remember - and she did I could see her hit my sister. Of course I run round don't
 
I - I said, don't you hit my sister like that. I said. And 'course - when I goes home - my old granny was a good woman. I said, 'ere gran, I said, that teacher at school has hit Lil round the ear, see. My father's coming through so - so he said, what did 
y
ou say? I said, nothing. He said, what did you say? I said, well, I said, that teacher at school, I said, been and hit our Lil round the ears. Oh, he said, did she? Said, I'll be up there see about it. Dad, don't come up, I said. He said, I'll be up there
.
 'Course I used to - being the monitor I used to - if anybody rung on the bell afternoon I used to have to go and - and one of the girls I used to sit with, old Ada Heath, I said, oh, I said, got an idea my dad's coming up today. I said, oh, I said, over 
m
y Lil this morning. All of a sudden the bell's gone see. She looked, she said, 'ere Rose, it's your dad. Cor, I said, I gets up, goes and opens the door, says, oh dad. It's all right, don't worry, don't worry, don't worry, you see. Goes in. So the headmis
t
ress said - who is it Rose? I said, it's my father. She said, your dad? She said, what for? Oh, I said, well he'll tell you. Of course she says, hello Mr O'Rorke. O'Rourke. O'Rourke. Hello Mr O'Rourke, she said. Well, he says, how comes that teacher hit m
y
 daughter round the ears? You know she's been under - operations with her ears, see. So she says, who? Well, he said, that's what my - my girl told me, my Rose, see. So of course she's had me in, said, Rose I want you. I said, yes, I went to put your pota
t
oes on, and, I said, I see - her hit my sister round - then I went round to her, see. Oh out comes her and that see. Yes, she said, admittedly I did. And my father said, don't ever hit my - daughter again because she's been under operations with her ears.
 
And if you look round - 'cos she did. She had a lump of - skin grafted from her thigh and put to the back of her ear see. She always suffered with her ears. So that was that. But - otherwise he - that's all I can ever remember him - standing up for us at 
- I suppose he would have done if we - but we never got in no bloody trouble. Ah well, that's all there is that kind of thing then So -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Do you ever remember him being out of work when you were a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Well - no, he was always in the - it wasn't
 much money like, but - he - although he went - he never give my mother no money. No. No. No, she was very lucky if she got any money off of him, I'll tell you that. She always had to go to work, my mother. Always. Worked hard. Seven - seven in the mornin
g to gone seven at night, and on a Saturday - she never got home 'til nearly half past eleven where they had to scrub all the stools in the restaurants before they come out. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Your mother worked in a restaurant?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 My mother worked hard. Yes, 
in - in Covent Garden. Yes. Yes. That was Mr Beadles. In Russell Street. Beadles in - Covent Garden. And they used to have - early morning breakfasts' was like - baked dinners and early morning she used to be in there and do 'em. Yes, that's where my aunt
 
worked for him, and my mother worked. Then when my aunt left - that's when I went and worked in Covent Garden for her then in a little coffee shop. She opened a little coffee shop and that's where I went and worked for her - when I was fourteen. Left scho
o
l. 'Cos I always wanted to go in the print. And my mother said, well go and help your aunt Rose out, she said, for a few weeks, and then - I'll see if I can get - I said, I don't want to go in the Garden, mum. That's how it was. That's how - so - she had 
t
he - coffee shop and I used to have to take - 'cos we only had a little - gas stove in like this little place, and I used to have to take - all the big meats and the - trays of potatoes down to Middlemass' in Covent Garden, he was - Middlemass' was the - 
b
akers and - in Floral Street, and he used to bake it all and - a certain time I used to go down and pick it up and - take it all through and - they used to carve it up for the dinners. But - oh yes, you can - it was a - very - you know, good life. You kno
w, happy life really, because - Covent Garden market was full of life, you know what I mean.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Your mother obviously worked hard when you were a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Yes. She did. She did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Is that the only job she did, do you remember her working anywhere else?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 
Oh yes, she had to - when - when - when Mr Beadle - give up the job, sold over she kept with a man and then - all of a sudden like she used to - because it was underground kitchen, and I used to go down to meet her like of a night, and - she sa
id, I don't know, she said, something wrong with the gas here. I said, well mum, be careful, 'cos, I said, if you go and open that oven, I said, you'll - it'll blow up in your face, see. Well, of course, this day she's there. And they - where they used to
 be was all the drippings and - down the walls and all that used to - be all wet on the ground, well they have to put all straw, see. Well of course she's gone to open the oven. This oven's half blew}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1461268\charrsid1983817  out, lit up with the other, bl}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 ew up, all the straws gone 
alight all in her face. Yes. Well of course they've - got a taxi haven't they, to take her to Charing Cross Hospital. Of course she had to have like a mask. Well of course the - the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1461268\charrsid1983817 \endash }{
