name here he said - cos - when she was away he said, you'd better have your fortnight's holiday, the guv'nor. You can have a fortnights holiday and five pound. Of course, she took that money. Them days, once you took any money you was done, she co
uld have - she could have claimed like - a lot of money but - not a lot of money like today but she could have but she never. And of course after that they sacked her. Well yes. Well of course I've got a job in - in - Cambridge Circus in the Cock Tavern. 
A
nd I'm the kitchen there see. And - I was veg cook. So - our cooks, I don't know what happened to her, I don't know, so - the missus said to me, got any idea - else who's - could take - will you take? No, I said. No. But I - you know, I wouldn't take on c
o
oking you see. I could have done but I - I wouldn't do it, see. No, I said, I'll tell you what. I said, my mum's out of work. I said, she's a cook, I said. All right, she said, fetch her over Sunday night to see me. I went over to her, I said, here mum, I
 
said, there's a job going if you like to take it on. She said, I've never been in a pub have I? I said, it don't matter about that, I said, you've got a - go with the times now. You're out of the market. I said, it'd be no - I said I'm in the - I'm in the
 
kitchen, I said. 'Cos my mother couldn't read or write you know see. And of course - she said, how will know like when the - well, I said, I'm - I'll take the tickets up you know and I could call you out. But she'd got a wonderful memory. Didn't matter ho
w
 many dinners you called out, as they come up, they come up how they was see. So - she said - I'll give it a week's trial, see. So she said, all right, I'll come with you. And I went over to see the missus. So, like, you know, she said, Else, she said, 'c
o
s her name was Rose, the Guv'nor said, better name you Else you see. So - so - so she said, all right, she said, well, I said, she's a bit nervous you know, I said. So she said, all right, she said, Else, tell your mum would she like to do it for a week's
 
trial, see. So - we got on all right and all that like you know, calling out. I said, mum do you think you'll - you'll like it? Oh she said, yes - yes I will. 'Cos we worked for a very - a very good guv'nor. His name was Ingham, it was his own pub really.
 
Right, the - Cock Tavern, Shaftesbury Avenue, opposite the Cambridge Theatre. So - good guv'nor. So - he said, all right, he said, Else, your mum's going to start. I said, yes. So - got on all right and that. Towards the Christmas time - we always had one
 
big room, it used to be the Buffaloes room on a Monday, but - it - it was let out for - all the girls in the pantomimes. And this year - this song, whenever it comes on the tele. When the Red Red Robin comes bob bob bobbing along. Well of course - they wa
s
 every day dancing, when the red, red robin comes bob, bob, bobbing along. Any old how one of the girls come out and said - 'course they never got paid them days while they was rehearsing see. She said, could you give me a glass of water? So - any old how
,
 our guv'nors gong through, so he said, what are you -oh, I said that girl wants a glass of - I said, they're drinking water all the time. Give 'em a pot of tea, he said. Give 'em a pot of tea, and - and do some bread and butter for 'em and take it in to 
'em, see. Which we - oh he was a good man. We took 'em into 'em. Can always remember that song when it comes on. When the red, red robin comes bob, bob, bobbing along. Them girls had to work hard them days.
