w him before, like when I was - knew him when I was fifteen, he was a few year older than me. He was in the Navy and - after that - after that - war was over like we - went out and after a time we - like got married. That was that but - he - he packed up 
- he come out the Navy, he packed up and then he went in Covent Garden market, but I lived with me - lived with me mother for a time and then I - left there and went and - like in a couple of rooms. And that's - that's that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Did you have to help your younger brother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 No, he died when he was - he died young. He died when he was about ten months old. No. There was only me and my sister. No, never.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Would you have to do things for your sister or would she do anything for you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 No, we all - 
we used to help one another. No. Help one another. And of course like my aunt, my youngest aunt, we - like she was a few years - younger than me, my mother's youngest sister, like, we used to all be practically at school together. Because like she got mar
ried in the '14 war but - but still stopped in like the house and of course then - when her baby was born I used to - practically look after him. And - at - at the finish he called me mum and called his mum May. Yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 What room would you bath in when you were young?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 
Oh - oh the old kitchen when we was young we used to have a big bath on the kitchen table and - my mother and granny used to see to us, every Friday night, we had our baths every Friday night and - we had our hair dine up in a -
 a - rag and that's all - Sunday morning and then pulled down and we used to have - like - nice big bow and all that - Sundays mornings, oh yes, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 When would you have clean clothes to put on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Every week. Every week. No, every week. My mu
m used to go to the baths so all our clothes was - ready to put on. Sunday mornings we used to have our change. Clean clothes all put on for - like you know. And we always had - a best - frock for Sunday and the best boots for Sunday, and the old pinafore
s you know that used to be. Frills all round here at the front and that, oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Where would you have your meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 We all used to - feed together in the kitchen. We all had a great - we had a - a big table that used to come up on a - a big fl
ap on a Sunday, pulled right out and we all used to sit round. My old grandfather used to carve the meat. And my old granny used to put all the vegetable all on and used to give it all round to us. 'Cos it used to go to the - we used to have like - always
 
having like plenty of baked potatoes we liked, it used - the oven used to hold so much and then my old grandfather used to take the meat and another load of baked potatoes round to the - bakers on a Sunday morning and they used to - give you a ticket, you
 used to go round about one o'clock to get it and - fetch it home and of course it was - oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Were there any occasions when you'd eat in any other room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Well all, no, we always ate in the kitchen, no. Unless there was a party and there was san
dwiches give out and it was in the - like what you call the front room and - they used to, you know, take the tray round with the plates and - you all helped yourselves for a meal, they put it on the table and you helped yourself from the plates. 'h no.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Where did your mother cook?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 
What - oh the - the - the - the gas stove. And then there was a - good kitchen - ah, my mother never - my mother went to work all the week, she never done no cooking on a Sunday, it was my granny. She done - yes, grann
y and grandfather, they - no, ; my mother - that was her - Sunday morning she always had a lay in, no, being at work all the week that - my old granny used to get on with the veg - grandfather always done the - if it was peas in or beans. Out in the old y
a
rd we used to have another - a table against the wall what you could put up with a long - spike. He used to get out there and peel all the potatoes, put in a bath under the cold water tap for Sunday and the - peas done and - that, whatever veg was going, 
well cook - cut the cabbage up Sunday mornings and throw in the - no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 When would you have breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Oh well, my grandfather used to fetch it up to bed. We all stopped in bed, he brought the breakfast up. He did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Was that every day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Oh
 no, no. I only said - on - only Sunday. Oh no, we used to go down like when we was at school, down - there used to be a boiled egg or perhaps - fried rasher or something like that. We always had something to go to school with, we never went without. No.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Was Sunday breakfast different?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 
No, well - no, it it was - might be kippers or a bit of haddock you know. Yes, oh yes, because - on a Saturday I used to go up what we called the smoke hole and I used to get a shillings worth of kippers and bloate
rs and haddocks. And - 'cos there - they put in so many, if they was a bit broke the k}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1461268\charrsid1983817 i}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 
ppers you had so many kippers - pairs of kippers put in, bloaters put in and - like the little haddocks. Smoked haddocks. Well you - you got a - you got a big koshel for
 about a shilling. Yes. You could all have a - you could all have a haddock and a poached egg on a Sunday morning. Eggs was about - what, yes, yes. And eggs then was about - I suppose - twenty-four for a shilling, 'cos they used to have 'em all in a great
 
big box opened up and you could - go and - you know - put 'em all in a basket and they'd come and - and then when it was pancake day you could go round the egg shop for cracked eggs. I - I have, I've took a great big basin round and got it filled up for s
i
xpence. Cracked eggs for - pancakes. You can go and get the lemons and they used to - my old grandfather used to make all the pancakes. Yes. Yes, pancakes. Used to go to school with a girl, she used to say, can I come home Rose? Yes. Old Ada, funny I ofte
n
 think of her. Can I come home? I used to say, gran can I fetch Ada Read home? Yes, I suppose you can, yes. Pancakes. 'Cos she was a - come from a big family and her mother - like she - like she aint never had no dad, her dad like died when they was young
. But - she always used to come home. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 What about the meal in the middle of the day, would you come home from school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Now - oh - our dinner was ready on the table, yes. We used to come home about - quarter past twelve I suppose. About quarte
r to one my granny used to put our - dinners up, had our dinner at quarter to one. Oh yes, always had a dinner and - our afters, always had a - a rice pudding or a - whatever was going, might be a bit of boiled duck, whatever they called it you know.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 What would you have for the first course usually, what sort of meals would you have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Well we used to have - perhaps a bit of - steak pie. Or a - stew. Steak and kidney pudding, yes, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 What about Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Oh - well - what - was roast b
eef. Roast lamb. Roast - it used to be - one Sunday used to be roast beef, baked potatoes, Yorkshire pudding. If it was roast lamb used to be a big - boiled - pudding like with the gravy on it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 What about tea, would you come home from school and have tea?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 
Oh yes, we always had like - bread and butter and - jam, marmalade and - perhaps sometimes my old grandfather used to get mussels, 'cos them days used to be - old boy used to come round with mussels lik}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1461268\charrsid1983817 e about three ha'pence a quarter}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 , he used t
o buy a big - little - well a little bath like that, had it filled up and he'd - he'd have 'em on and you'd have mussels for your tea and - but - oh yes, we always had like a - little relish of some sort. No, we - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Would your mother eat when she came in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Not 'til the night time, she had her supper with her - half a pint of - porter or - them days when I was a child.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Did you ever sing together round the piano?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Oh no, no, no, no, no. Not - when Christmas was on we all used to be sing
ing, know what I mean, but - never stood round the - I think me and my sister once stood and - I forget the song now. We stood and sang a - old song, I can't think of it now. But - not for us all to stand round the piano to sing. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Would your grandparents or mother ever play any games with you girls?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 
Oh no, well my mother - my mother used to, you know, come home and sometimes, she had to stand ironing and - oh no, my mother could never - play games. Oh I know my old grandfather generally used 
to chop all the wood up like for the - winter and all that and - me and my sister used to have the whole - logs stood on the side, we used to think - we used to make out we were selling kippers and bloaters and we'd have bits of paper and put the kippers 
and bloaters in like we used to - you'd go and buy the kippers and bloaters, no, no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Were there any books in your house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 No. Oh no. Oh we - perhaps have a couple of - oh comics or - couple of - story books, I forget now but - no, we never had
 a lot of books, no. Although we - we went to school, we was - you know - well I left in standard seven so them days - it was a - a good - a good - standard to leave in. My sister was a bit backward because she - she always suffered with her ears, she'd b
e
en under - bad operations with her ears and been away - like months from school that she was a bit backward that - but otherwise - we - we - like knew our drill. Well I finished up - the champion swimmer at the school when I left at fourteen. And I learnt
 my sister to swim. 'Cos they would never allow her to go swimming from school 'cos of her ears, well I took her and - I used to take her when I used to go like swimming of a night. I used to take her, that's how she learnt to swim but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Did you have swimming lessons from school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 
Yes. I - no, we learnt from - like we used to go to the baths and learnt - the - swimming teacher at the baths, used to be a swimming teacher at the baths.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 After school that would be in your own time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 No, that - no, that was - like from - from school we used to go.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 As a proper lesson?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Yes, oh yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Would you have any newspapers, would your grandfather read a newspaper each day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Oh well, they used to read the papers but we - we never 
had no - we never - 'cos them days used to be like a pink paper used to be with all the murders in that you wasn't - you wasn't allowed - no, not that, we could have a - buy such as a - one of my aunts used to have the Woman's - a little - a book like tha
t
, the Woman's Own or something, used to be about tuppence and - it - it told you how to make cakes and all that, that's how she learnt when she - like - 'cos she never could cook but that's how she learnt to make cakes and - all that when she got married.
 
But otherwise - although we used to go to - we used to go to cookery at school. And what else was it we used to go. Oh used to go laundry at school. Yes, used to have to take something to wash and iron you know and - then we used to go - to cookery and we
 used to - if it was pancake day we used to have to make a pancake you know that - yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 So girls were taught home making?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Yes. All that, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Do you remember your mother or father reading much?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Well my mother couldn't read or wri
te. No, no. It was only after - years after when - she - like packed up you know and they paid her off her job and she went - she went on the labour and I took her up the Labour and - and I said to the lady - lady - woman behind the - said, my mum can't r
e
ad or write, I said. She said, all right, she said, not to worry, 'cos my mother said, I don't know whether I'm going to - I'm not going. I said, you go up mum and get a few shillings, I said, and - like - put a cross, you know, she - and after a time I s
aid to, come on, you try and write your name. Towards the end she could just write Topsy Rourke. Yes, she done that at the end, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 People didn't have the opportunities in those days did they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 No, she - well she went to school when she was nine 
- she went to work when she was nine. Had to go out, yes. Yes. Yes, my - my granny had - well - to the average I think my granny had about twenty-four children by the way that - like she spoke. But - had one child every eleven months. And I mean them days
 you had to look after your own children, you never had the help what you get today. Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Would you ever read to your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Oh no, my granny used to. Yes, now and a - like of a night, you know, well we used to have to go up to bed or that and
 - but she used to sit down and read to her and all that you know that - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Do you ever remember any funerals in your family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 No. Oh no, only when my aunt lost a little boy, yes, a baby that - that was buried but - no, can't say we did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 You all went to that funeral did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 
Oh no. No. No. I didn't, no, not me, no. Not - my mother and granny did and like the father and mother but - oh no, 'cos it was only a young baby. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Do you remember if people used to wear mourning clothes at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 
Yes. Widows had long - long veils right down the back and all crepe all down here to the ankles. They - they wore 'em to - for twelve months. Yes, all deep crepe. Was terrible.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 So you could pick out a widow in the streets?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Yes. Yes, well she had a long black veil at the back. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 And people weren't allowed to go out much in mourning?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 No. Yes, oh yes. Yes, oh yes. 'Course the - today they're more - they're more - what you can call - well I don't know, they're mo
re - they're not so - what can I say, they're not so - narrow minded. Years - years ago - 'ere - years ago if a girl got into trouble, my God she had to go - miles away out of it. Now look at today. Oh dear, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 I think this is a better attitude don't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 
Well I think so. Well all I can say that - you can always say like - if you've got a girl and like she's got into trouble you can always forgive her for the - first one, 'cos you never know that - you know, I'm not going to say - when they had 
- second or that, but - like - one, you - you can because you never know - you know - how it's occurred or what way or anything like that but - oh God. Well you - now you're talking about that, a girl I used to go with like when I was - well, I think I wa
s fifteen, and - 'cos she used to - like go out and all that you know, but - and - when I see her she said, 'ere, she said, Rose, she said, I want - I believe I'm going to have}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1461268\charrsid1983817 
