\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 You were going from one end of London to the other weren't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 To the other, yes, we used to have to - go over the bridge, see. But - I know we used to get to Hampstead, but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Would your mother have the day off on a Bank Holiday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 On a Bank Holiday, yes. Yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Did you ever go away on any other holidays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Oh a 
fortnight's - fortnight's holiday from school, we used to have to pay in for it what they called the Bank Holiday Fund. We went away, yes, me and my sister and - 'cos then like my aunt, she was - only a few years - well she wasn't a lot older - wasn't a l
o
t older than me. My mother's youngest sister. And we all - we all went away Bank Holiday - for a fortnights holiday and that's when - my old granny, God rest her - always said, now all try and keep together, the three of you keep together, you see. 'Cours
e
 when we got there - like - we got - somebody said, I'll take her. And I'll take these two, see, 'cos - I said, we mustn't - we mustn't be parted, we've all - so - I don't know, a woman said, three of you can't go together. Oh 'course they've took me and 
m
y sister here, our May's gone somewhere else. I've cried me eyes out all night can't I, 'cos we're all - although she come round and the woman used to be very good and - but - we got used to her after but the first week we - 'cos we was - 'cos - with us i
ndoors, like we all slept together in the room, you know. Me and my - me and my sister slept in one bed and like the aunt, we never called her that, we always called her our May, always slept in like another bed in the room - but - always together.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 What place did you go to that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Oh we went down Reading way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 It was always to the country?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Oh down, yes, we went down the line, yes. Went down the line, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Would you go every year on these school holidays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Oh yes, if - like 
fortnight. Oh a - a fortnight we went, yes, we used to go - like from school, pay in like, my mother used to pay in or my aunt paid in for us to go. Fortnight's holiday, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Did your mother ever have a holiday way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 No. My old mum, no. No, in the later years, me and her went away, but - no, my mother never, she worked too hard, my poor old mum. Never.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 What would you do when you were on these school holidays, were you left to yourselves or did they organise you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 What, when we was awa
y? Oh no, you just - well we used to go out and - and I know near where we was there was a great big field, we used to go out and - we used to - and I did because - really with me - I suppose - I was such a home bird, I remember I used to sit on this seat
 and see - I used to see the trains go by. I used to sing, take me back to London. I used to sit there crying he blo}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13847602\charrsid1983817 o}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 
dy eyes out. Oh dear. Yes. No, me, I was a home bird. Although we had some - very good people you know but - especially of a night, I - when
 it was time to go to bed. Oh I used to say to my sister - my sister, she'd go to bed at five o'clock at night. It wouldn't worry her. But I wouldn't, I wouldn't go to bed, if they - I could stop up 'til twelve o'clock at night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 You were used to having your family around you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Yes. Oh yes. Yes. No, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 What would you do on a Saturday when you were a girl?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Oh we used to go to the pictures, what they called the - we used to pay about a penny or tuppence round the pictures. Might take some
 - sweets and all that and that used to be for about - suppose - twelve o'clock 'til about - two o'clock I suppose. 'Cos in our house on Saturday we had what we called tea and dinner together so - you know, was eggs and bacon or whatever it was and someth
i
ng else and chips or something that - we had it - that - just that was on a Saturday. Then - or Friday nights we always had our baths. Every Friday night our bath, and our hair used to be done up in ringlets 'til Sunday morning you know. Yes. All day Satu
rday. When they come out they was all long curls, yes. Yes. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Did you mind having them in all day Saturday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Well it was - you never really took no notice of it but - 'cos them days it was a - recognized thing, the children - you know, like th
e mother's that - like looked after - or some mothers didn't care whether their girls hair was straight, whether it was any way but - oh my mother, no. Your hair was always in ringlets. Two big bows. My hair was parted in the middle, two big bows. My sist
er's parted at the side. One big bow. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 That was for Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Sundays, yes, and your - your - you know, your pinafore all frilled up and - that was your Sunday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 You always wore different clothes on Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Sunday. Sundays and - you a
lways had new clothes for - Easter, Whitsun, you know, and Christmas, oh you had your - rig-out for Christmas. Yes. New coat, you know, whatever was going like. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 What would you do on a Sunday in your family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Well used to get up and have o
ur breakfast and - 'course - as I got older - my sister one had to do the lavatory, one had to do the passage and the front, another one had to clean the knives and forks and - cut up the beetroot for the Sunday dinnertime. And then you had to - like you 
got dressed and then you - after dinner you went to - school - Sunday school. Yes. You always had to go to Sunday school after dinner.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Most children went to Sunday school those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Oh yes. Yes. Yes. Had to go to Sunday school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Did your parents or grandmother or grandfather go to church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 
Oh my old granny used to go to - not my mother, she was always at work, nor my father or - not my grandfather but - my old granny used to go what they called the Mothers Meeting years ago, like - all l
ike - the women used to go like and have a cup of tea and sit like the old vicar I suppose, I don't know. It was always called a Mothers Meeting, I don't know, I never -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Your grandmother didn't go to church much?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Oh no, no, no. No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 What sort of Sunday school did you go to, did you go to a Church of England one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 
Oh yes, Church of - what was it - oh yes, yes, like - well, used to be the old chapel in the - bottom of the street, what we called the chapel. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Did you go on Sunday school outings, would they provide an outing for you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 
I can't really - recall that, not Sunday school outing. I don't think - that was a - just like a chapel and I don't think - not that - I don't remember ever going to a; outing with them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Did you take part in any other activities organised by the church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Oh no, no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 You weren't in the choir?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Do you know if your church ran any temperance clubs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Oh - I don't know, I couldn't tell you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 You weren't a member of one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 You didn't sign the pledge or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 No. Oh no, I was never - I was never - well - being truthful I was never interested in that kind of thing, know what I mean, that - oh no.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Did you belong to any other clubs of any sort?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 No. No, not as - that I could - no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Would your family say grace at meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 
Oh no, no. Oh you said, thank God for your good dinner. Oh, you know, like, thank God for a good dinner, or my old grandfather used to say a, thank God for our good dinner, like he did, oh yes, yes. No. No we never said, grace, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Were you taught to say prayers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Oh when we was children we used to - you know - God bless dad, God bless mum and - that was in early like but -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Did you have any family prayers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Oh no, no. No. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Do - you remember your father taking an interest in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Oh - oh no, no, not him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Grandfather?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 No, no. No, no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 He never talked about voting and what party he voted for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Oh 
- oh he used to be a - he was a - an Labour man, my grandfather. Oh yes. Yes. The blue. When it - like, you know, voting like is blue ain't it. Is it blue now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Do you remember which colour he would have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Oh - red I think, red then. Oh he was a - no, he was a -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Would he be a Liberal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 No, no. No, he was a Labour man. No, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Did he used to talk about politics much?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Oh no. No. Oh we never - if he did he never spoke - he never said anything in front of us as children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Do you think your grandmother was interested?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 
Oh no, well - no, well they used to - abide by what the men said didn't they. They never - they never like today like the girls do today or the women today, if they think they'll vote for something they'll vot
e if they - whether their husband's the other way round, you know. No, oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Would your grandfather vote?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Oh used to go and vote. Yes. Can always remember him going voting, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Do you think your grandmother did when women got the vote, would she have gone and voted in 1919?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 1919? I can't really say that - not with that, 1919, well I was nineteen then. No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid752558 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Do you think she'd have voted the same way as your grandfather?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8213171 FJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 Oh she'd have gone his way. Well that's - 'cos she nev
er really knew - my granny could never read or write, she learnt herself to read my granny and she learnt herself to write. Towards the end. How she used to write was - she'd say something, she'd write that, and what she said - something else was under th
a
t way, you know, she - she learnt, yes she did, she learnt. 'Cos like - when my uncle - when my uncle was in the Navy he used to - like send - send her something home you know, and she always said to me, don't let your mother know that Uncle Dan has sent 
s
omething home to me. Yes, you know. Yes. And - her - and my mother - well my mother said, well as I got older my mother said, I don't know, she said, I don't know why - Uncle Dan don't send mum any money. See. So she said, I think I'll get you to send him
 
a letter, see. 'Cos - my mother couldn't write see. Oh - so mum, I said, before I write to Uncle Dan, I said, got something to tell you. I said, granny gets a - granny gets a letter, I said, she gets - I think it was about a dollar you know, five shilling
s
 and - I said, don't say I said, she - I said, she's told me not to tell you. You know, me being near - indoors you know and it - 'cos it happened to be one day I'd got the letter and I said, there's a letter for you gran, you know. I said, all right, I'l
l
 open it for you, being nosey like. I'll read it to you. Don't have to, she said, don't have to. But - 'course I opened it didn't I. Oh, I said, there's - something from Uncle Dan, it was in - in the Navy. My - well my mother told her - she told her. So m
um you never had - 'cos my mum was a very good woman you know. My mother was, she was a good woman my mother. She used to pay for all the coal, used to pay the - rent of the house. She never used to leave the coal though 'cos we}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967946\charrsid1983817  used to have the coal from Lebo}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10178391\charrsid1983817 
ns then days, you - you used to have a ton in at a time and you paid so much a week. 'Cos our - our coal cellar went under the stairs, it held a ton of coal. And we used to have it from Lebons, and then - Lebons used to be a - a very big coal merchants 
see. Well nearly everybody that - they'd have 'em from Lebons, pay so much for a ton. Well half a ton or what they called a quarter of a ton, five bags, ten bags, twenty bags, whatever it was. We always had a ton in, went right under the coal cellar. My m
other used to leave the money out - such as Wednesday, whenever it was - the - you know, the - insurance or rent, she left that every - my old mum, very good woman.
